From: johnsonfarmsus
Subject: [PATCH] ml/device: skip GGML_CUDA_INIT deep-init validation

AddInitValidation sets GGML_CUDA_INIT=1, which triggers rocblas_initialize()
during the discovery sub-process. The intent is to crash the runner on
unsupported devices so they get filtered out of the candidate list.

This works against us in two cases:
  1. When parent env pins ROCR_VISIBLE_DEVICES to a known-good iGPU, the
     validation can still crash if the bundled rocBLAS lacks kernels for
     the specific arch (this is true for gfx1103 with mainline ROCm).
  2. When the user has supplemented system rocBLAS with kernels for the
     target arch (e.g. dropping in Fedora's gfx1103 Tensile files), the
     "deep init crash detection" is redundant — the real test is whether
     model load succeeds.

With this patched out, devices that fail at actual model load still get
caught (Ollama logs the runner termination), and devices that work get
to run.

---
 ml/device.go | 2 +-
 1 file changed, 1 insertion(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/ml/device.go b/ml/device.go
--- a/ml/device.go
+++ b/ml/device.go
@@ -557,7 +557,7 @@ func (d DeviceInfo) NeedsInitValidation() bool {

 // Set the init validation environment variable
 func (d DeviceInfo) AddInitValidation(env map[string]string) {
-	env["GGML_CUDA_INIT"] = "1" // force deep initialization to trigger crash on unsupported GPUs
+	// env["GGML_CUDA_INIT"] = "1" // patched out — parent ROCR_VISIBLE_DEVICES handles filtering
 }

 // PreferredLibrary returns true if this library is preferred over the other input
